<subSubSection id="97F923FF71EDE1E39CF6E34C2E44773E" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="6F172CE096BF83F14B202D569962574A" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="34EE1DCAA1EC852CA2A72C27A5D5BF78" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">
<taxonomicName id="55E6EC10063558A6CF95566A17ECDF9E" authorityName="J. R. I. Wood &amp; Scotland" authorityYear="2017" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Ipomoea" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Ipomoea walteri" order="Solanales" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="walteri">
<emphasis id="EEEA9D1505EDDC1C834B140B713AD24B" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Ipomoea walteri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is close to 
<taxonomicName id="4803CFBEAAD605CEC70C981AE5000E56" genus="I." lsidName="I. sericophylla" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" rank="species" species="sericophylla">
<emphasis id="15FD262F1DD97A9AF6521350C353A34D" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">I. sericophylla</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but distinct because of the long-pedunculate lax inflorescence, adaxially nearly glabrous leaves and unequal sepals, the inner noticeably shorter than the outer. Particularly distinct are the strongly cuspidate leaves with a distinct apical mucro c. 3 mm long which is only matched in a few very different species, such as 
<taxonomicName id="DD5C063BED0F7B9F7617E2D0D0776379" genus="I." lsidName="I. daturiflora" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" rank="species" species="daturiflora">
<emphasis id="BA6699F1010A56CE87F2CD636B9B91E8" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">I. daturiflora</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Meisn.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
